and to help you all out.

00:01:56.590 --> 00:02:00.600
But let's introduce our speakers.

00:02:00.600 --> 00:02:02.220
So, Domenica Marchetti.

00:02:02.220 --> 00:02:05.770
Domenica Marchetti grew
up in an Italian family.

00:02:05.770 --> 00:02:09.460
Her mother is from
Chieti, in Abruzzo.

00:02:09.460 --> 00:02:14.740
And of her family, Domenica
says, "At the dinner table,

00:02:14.740 --> 00:02:18.630
we spent more time talking about
what we should eat the next day,

00:02:18.630 --> 00:02:22.070
rather than politics and
the news of the day."

00:02:22.070 --> 00:02:24.130
I can relate, being Italian.

00:02:24.130 --> 00:02:27.560
But I have to say that I had some
of my best political discussions

00:02:27.560 --> 00:02:30.320 position:56%
with my father, at the dinner table.

00:02:30.320 --> 00:02:34.550
Domenica refers to
another experience.

00:02:34.550 --> 00:02:41.520
She says that her mother had her
sister and her shaping gnocchi

00:02:41.520 --> 00:02:45.480
and ravioli by the time they could
see over the kitchen counter.

00:02:45.480 --> 00:02:51.810
This too, is a very common
experience in Italian families.

00:02:51.810 --> 00:02:55.650
Domenica graduated from
Columbia's School of Journalism.

00:02:55.650 --> 00:02:58.980
Started her career as
a newspaper reporter.

00:02:58.980 --> 00:03:03.500
And wrote about a lot of topics,
until she realized that writing

00:03:03.500 --> 00:03:06.680
