00:07:11.950 --> 00:07:14.750
to speak about Italian food.

00:07:14.750 --> 00:07:17.060
Which is a subject near
and dear to my heart.

00:07:17.060 --> 00:07:19.830
I have seven books
on Italian cooking.

00:07:19.830 --> 00:07:22.660
So it's something I think
about pretty much 24-7.

00:07:22.660 --> 00:07:28.270
And I was thinking about
the theme of this week,

00:07:28.270 --> 00:07:30.010
Italian Food in the World.

00:07:30.010 --> 00:07:32.270
Italian Cuisine in the World.

00:07:32.270 --> 00:07:35.020
And so I'm just going to give
you a little bit of an overview

00:07:35.020 --> 00:07:37.140
on my thoughts on that subject.

00:07:37.140 --> 00:07:41.480
And then Amy has prepared a
wonderful PowerPoint presentation

00:07:41.480 --> 00:07:42.780
for us.

00:07:42.780 --> 00:07:46.820
I was thinking about my most
recent book, <i>Preserving Italy</i>.

00:07:46.820 --> 00:07:50.500
And the double entendre is
definitely on purpose there,

00:07:50.500 --> 00:07:51.920
in the title of the book.

00:07:51.920 --> 00:07:53.900
On the surface, it's a book

00:07:53.900 --> 00:07:57.240
about Italian preserving
traditions in the kitchen.

00:07:57.240 --> 00:07:59.460
[ Foreign Language ]

00:07:59.460 --> 00:08:02.750
So foods preserved in oil,
foods preserved in vinegar.

00:08:02.750 --> 00:08:07.300
Marmalade's, jams, fruit
pastes, syrups, liquors.

00:08:07.300 --> 00:08:12.600
Everything from those things
to fresh cheeses and salami.

00:08:12.600 --> 00:08:16.590
Because if you think of the Italian
table, so many foods that come

00:08:16.590 --> 00:08:19.590
to the Italian table, are
foods that have been preserved.

00:08:19.590 --> 00:08:24.510
Preserving the bounty
of Italian ingredients.

00:08:24.510 --> 00:08:27.780
And even if you're not Italian,
chances are, you are familiar

00:08:27.780 --> 00:08:29.110
with most of these foods.

00:08:29.110 --> 00:08:32.070
If you go to just about
any supermarket these days,

00:08:32.070 --> 00:08:34.230
you will find jars of Giardiniera.

00:08:34.230 --> 00:08:39.210 position:56%
Or roasted peppers, or, pancetta and
guanciale in the deli department.

00:08:39.210 --> 00:08:42.300
When I was growing up,
these things were not quite

00:08:42.300 --> 00:08:43.620
as common as they are now.

00:08:43.620 --> 00:08:45.700 position:56%
But they are pretty much everywhere.

00:08:45.700 --> 00:08:51.530
But beyond that, the book is also
about preserving these traditions.

00:08:51.530 --> 00:08:55.600
These ways, these food ways,
these ways of these techniques.

00:08:55.600 --> 00:09:00.400
And, you know, the world is
ever-changing, Italy is changing.

00:09:00.400 --> 00:09:04.290
And so it was important to me, as
somebody who loves Italian cuisine,

00:09:04.290 --> 00:09:07.410
to try to maybe bottle
some of these recipes

00:09:07.410 --> 00:09:10.090
and old traditions in this book.

00:09:10.090 --> 00:09:14.580
I have to say, though, ultimately,
it's a kind of a futile endeavor,

00:09:14.580 --> 00:09:16.870
because food is always evolving.

00:09:16.870 --> 00:09:19.400
Cuisine is always evolving.

00:09:19.400 --> 00:09:22.840
And when you think about
Italian food in the world,

00:09:22.840 --> 00:09:25.410
you know, you really do see that.

00:09:25.410 --> 00:09:27.740
And the more I thought
about this subject,

00:09:27.740 --> 00:09:29.970
the more I realized
that Italian food.

00:09:29.970 --> 00:09:32.000
Or the food of the
peninsula, I should say,

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:33.860
before there was an Italy.

00:09:33.860 --> 00:09:37.960
There's always been the food of the
Italian peninsula out in the world.

00:09:37.960 --> 00:09:42.530 position:56%
Whether it was through the spread of
the Roman Empire, to food traditions

00:09:42.530 --> 00:09:45.460
that traveled to France
with Caterina de' Medici.

00:09:45.460 --> 00:09:50.810
And also the foods that Thomas
Jefferson introduced to the U.S.

00:09:50.810 --> 00:09:52.640
after traveling to Italy.

00:09:52.640 --> 00:09:58.060
Including pasta, or
macaroni, gelato, ice cream,

00:09:58.060 --> 00:10:00.760
and even rice he brought back.

00:10:00.760 --> 00:10:05.440
Nowadays, we have chefs who,
you know, even here in D.C.,

00:10:05.440 --> 00:10:08.780
who travel to Italy in
search of authentic recipes.

00:10:08.780 --> 00:10:12.040
And they bring them back to their
own restaurants here in the U.S.,

00:10:12.040 --> 00:10:14.220
and elsewhere in the world.

00:10:14.220 --> 00:10:16.520
So that's a little
bit of an overview

00:10:16.520 --> 00:10:18.420
about Italian food in the world.

00:10:18.420 --> 00:10:20.280
But, as I was thinking of
the subject, I thought,

00:10:20.280 --> 00:10:22.540
you know, it's not just that.

00:10:22.540 --> 00:10:26.810
If you turn it around, you
have the world in Italian food,

00:10:26.810 --> 00:10:28.980
or the world of Italian food.

00:10:28.980 --> 00:10:33.600
And so that's kind of looking at
things in a different perspective.

00:10:33.600 --> 00:10:36.660
There's always been a
cross-cultural influences

00:10:36.660 --> 00:10:40.030
in what we broadly refer
to as Italian cuisine.

00:10:40.030 --> 00:10:44.050
Whether this is a result
of war, invasion, religion,

00:10:44.050 --> 00:10:46.140
migration, travel, and so on.

00:10:46.140 --> 00:10:48.350
So, you know, you think
about Sicilian food.

00:10:48.350 --> 00:10:52.400
And the influence of
Arab and African culture

00:10:52.400 --> 00:10:55.230
and ingredients on
the food of Sicily.

00:10:55.230 --> 00:10:58.470
And you think of the New World,
and the ingredients brought

00:10:58.470 --> 00:11:00.410
from the New World back to Italy.

00:11:00.410 --> 00:11:03.010
Potatoes, peppers, tomatoes.

00:11:03.010 --> 00:11:06.870
I mean, to me, the aroma of roasted
peppers is the aroma of Italy.

00:11:06.870 --> 00:11:10.640
But, of course, and you know,
in the history of the world,

00:11:10.640 --> 00:11:14.520
peppers are a pretty recent
introduction into the cuisine

00:11:14.520 --> 00:11:16.500
of the Italian Peninsula.

00:11:16.500 --> 00:11:22.050
So, and in the 18th
and 19th century,

00:11:22.050 --> 00:11:25.160
we had the so-called
British invasion of Italy.

00:11:25.160 --> 00:11:29.440
Where a lot of British people you
know, the poets, the romantics,

00:11:29.440 --> 00:11:32.560
moved to Italy, wrote about
the Italian landscape.

00:11:32.560 --> 00:11:35.400
And they brought with them,
things like roast beef.

00:11:35.400 --> 00:11:38.160 position:56%
So even today, if you go to Tuscany,

00:11:38.160 --> 00:11:41.060
you can find in the
trattorias, roast beef.

00:11:41.060 --> 00:11:47.610
Which is, basically, you know, the
Tuscan variation of a British food.

00:11:47.610 --> 00:11:50.250
So all of these things were kind
of rolling around in my head.

00:11:50.250 --> 00:11:53.440
And it's a very complex
subject, as we know.

00:11:53.440 --> 00:11:56.670
And, as I was thinking of it,
I thought of my friend Amy,

00:11:56.670 --> 00:12:00.210
who is a food historian
and a cookbook author.

00:12:00.210 --> 00:12:03.300
And just a really a
font of knowledge

00:12:03.300 --> 00:12:04.900
on the history of Italian cuisine.

00:12:04.900 --> 00:12:08.410
So I asked her to come with me
and delve into this subject today.

00:12:08.410 --> 00:12:11.200
And she's prepared a wonderful
PowerPoint, which we're going

00:12:11.200 --> 00:12:13.330
