00:24:30.260 --> 00:24:32.780
When they wanted to have something
luxurious, they added spice,

00:24:32.780 --> 00:24:34.310
because it showed that
they had money.

00:24:34.310 --> 00:24:35.610
Spice was a form of currency.

00:24:35.610 --> 00:24:38.500
Spice was used as a
traditional medicinal.

00:24:38.500 --> 00:24:41.920
Spice was used as a show of
wealth, as a mood enhancer,

00:24:41.920 --> 00:24:43.220
all kinds of different things.

00:24:43.220 --> 00:24:47.470
But at that time, Venice and
Istanbul, over top right,

00:24:47.470 --> 00:24:49.470
and Cairo, were all sister cities.

00:24:49.470 --> 00:24:51.770
And they were all involved
in the spice trade.

00:24:51.770 --> 00:24:54.300
All of those cities, the things
would go around and around.

00:24:54.300 --> 00:24:56.390
The merchants would just keep
bringing them back and forth.

00:24:56.390 --> 00:24:58.510 position:56%
Were all built pretty much on spice.

00:24:58.510 --> 00:25:00.250
All of the beauty that, you
know, all of the grandeur,

00:25:00.250 --> 00:25:03.830
all of the wonderful wealth that
is hard to even comprehend today.

00:25:03.830 --> 00:25:05.770
Maybe we would think
about it with petroleum.

00:25:05.770 --> 00:25:07.530
They were all built on spice.

00:25:07.530 --> 00:25:09.730
One of the unique things that
happened, though, to Venice,

00:25:09.730 --> 00:25:11.820
in terms, that didn't
happen to other cities.

00:25:11.820 --> 00:25:14.970
Was when the Dutch later on found
a new trade route to the east,

00:25:14.970 --> 00:25:16.440
they didn't need these
cities anymore.

00:25:16.440 --> 00:25:17.740
So they were all going
to go bankrupt.

00:25:17.740 --> 00:25:19.040
And they knew.

00:25:19.040 --> 00:25:20.340
There was like a little
bit of advanced warning,

00:25:20.340 --> 00:25:21.640
that they all knew they
were going to suffer

00:25:21.640 --> 00:25:22.940
from these new trade routes.

00:25:22.940 --> 00:25:24.240
And not needing the Mediterranean
and the Middle East anymore.

00:25:24.240 --> 00:25:26.140
But what the Venetians
did was really cool was,

00:25:26.140 --> 00:25:28.280
they took the residual
money that they had.

00:25:28.280 --> 00:25:29.580
And instead of holding onto it

00:25:29.580 --> 00:25:31.170
because they were going
to go bankrupt.

00:25:31.170 --> 00:25:32.710
They actually spent
it on the frescoes

00:25:32.710 --> 00:25:34.010
that you can see on the canal.

00:25:34.010 --> 00:25:36.820
So all of this additional
beauty came out of a time

00:25:36.820 --> 00:25:38.900
that most people would have been
really worried about failure.

00:25:38.900 --> 00:25:41.340
And then, of course, Venice became
a popular tourist destination,

00:25:41.340 --> 00:25:42.930
because it was so beautiful.

00:25:42.930 --> 00:25:46.380
So it helped us to kind of, you
know, live through that moment.

00:25:46.380 --> 00:25:49.590
And it's a really good
example of food and culture,

00:25:49.590 --> 00:25:51.520
and kind of cities in the world.

00:25:51.520 --> 00:25:53.620
Then again, we have to
talk about Da Vinci.

00:25:53.620 --> 00:25:56.250
Because -- and I would've
loved to talk about,

00:25:56.250 --> 00:25:57.690
you know, 500 different figures.

00:25:57.690 --> 00:25:59.750
But, to just choose
one, this is important.

00:25:59.750 --> 00:26:03.560
Because in the 15th century,
and the 16th century.

00:26:03.560 --> 00:26:05.690
When you're looking at all
of these titles that had --

00:26:05.690 --> 00:26:06.990
Lucia was making fun of me.

00:26:06.990 --> 00:26:09.230
Because I have three slashes
in my professional title.

00:26:09.230 --> 00:26:11.440
But look at his, and
they were all like that.

00:26:11.440 --> 00:26:13.030
And it wasn't the first
time, you know.

00:26:13.030 --> 00:26:14.800
There were many, many people
during the Renaissance.

00:26:14.800 --> 00:26:16.540
Hence, the term Renaissance man.

00:26:16.540 --> 00:26:18.930
In two centuries prior, in Baghdad,

00:26:18.930 --> 00:26:21.010
many of those scholars
were also like that.

00:26:21.010 --> 00:26:22.400
They had all these same things.

00:26:22.400 --> 00:26:26.040 position:56%
And so, as we were taking many ideas
from the east, so was this idea

00:26:26.040 --> 00:26:27.730
of being able to do many things.

00:26:27.730 --> 00:26:29.030
Of expanding the mind.

00:26:29.030 --> 00:26:30.330
Of no limits.

00:26:30.330 --> 00:26:31.710
Of not having to be so focused.

00:26:31.710 --> 00:26:35.000
Of science, and knowledge, and
learning, and math, and food.

00:26:35.000 --> 00:26:36.480
And all being intertwined.

00:26:36.480 --> 00:26:39.340
We also see more formal
ways of writing

00:26:39.340 --> 00:26:41.150
about food and appreciating food.

00:26:41.150 --> 00:26:43.690
Because, for a while, you know,
that food was just something

00:26:43.690 --> 00:26:45.210
that you would talk
about for the wealthy.

00:26:45.210 --> 00:26:46.760
For the upper-class.

00:26:46.760 --> 00:26:48.270
For the people in the palaces.

00:26:48.270 --> 00:26:51.380
And now we start to see it really
being looked at as a science.

00:26:51.380 --> 00:26:54.280
And it's thanks to people
like this, in addition to all

00:26:54.280 --> 00:26:58.140
of the many wonderful advancements
that they made in society.

00:26:58.140 --> 00:27:00.120
And then, as Domenica
mentioned, Columbus.

00:27:00.120 --> 00:27:01.760
And, of course, coming
to the New World.

00:27:01.760 --> 00:27:04.810
And regardless of the individual
that came, or, you know,

00:27:04.810 --> 00:27:06.260
what the reasons behind that were.

00:27:06.260 --> 00:27:09.740
There was definitely, with the
Spanish, all of this influx

00:27:09.740 --> 00:27:11.590
of new ingredients
that came to Italy.

00:27:11.590 --> 00:27:15.220
And Italy really, really
embraced every single one.

00:27:15.220 --> 00:27:18.970
What's interesting is some of --
because of the Turkish influence.

00:27:18.970 --> 00:27:21.620
And the Turks were in charge
of a lot of trade at the time.

00:27:21.620 --> 00:27:25.380
A lot of the products that were
new into Italy, got Turkish names.

00:27:25.380 --> 00:27:27.680
So like, you know, products
that are made with corn a lot

00:27:27.680 --> 00:27:29.920
of times get called [foreign
word], or Turkish grain.

00:27:29.920 --> 00:27:31.280
And it has nothing
to do with Turkey,

00:27:31.280 --> 00:27:32.870
other than that the
Turks were the middlemen.

00:27:32.870 --> 00:27:35.130
Turkish coffee, you know, they
didn't get the coffee from Turkey,

00:27:35.130 --> 00:27:36.430
but they were bringing it around.

00:27:36.430 --> 00:27:37.730
So it got labeled as Turkish.

00:27:37.730 --> 00:27:39.920
And so we see these words
a lot of times in Italy.

00:27:39.920 --> 00:27:42.350
And it, you know, up
until very recently,

00:27:42.350 --> 00:27:45.120
if someone in a very small
community came from another place.

00:27:45.120 --> 00:27:48.180 position:56%
A lot of French people called them a
Turk, because they came from a part.

00:27:48.180 --> 00:27:51.180
So you can't always use
etymology in food history.

00:27:51.180 --> 00:27:52.920
Sometimes it leads you
to something different.

00:27:52.920 --> 00:27:56.240 position:56%
It's just a little provincial thing.

00:27:56.240 --> 00:28:01.110
We have corn, tomatoes, potatoes,
vanilla, avocados, peppers.

00:28:01.110 --> 00:28:03.970
All kinds of things
coming from the New World.

00:28:03.970 --> 00:28:06.490
And here's an example of, you
know, some different dishes.

00:28:06.490 --> 00:28:08.110
This one is a [foreign
word] dish on the left.

00:28:08.110 --> 00:28:10.900
They have a saying that if
it has peppers, and tomatoes,

00:28:10.900 --> 00:28:12.750
and onions, it's [foreign word].

00:28:12.750 --> 00:28:16.110
But, as we can see, a lot of
those ingredients, you know,

00:28:16.110 --> 00:28:18.600
two of those ingredients, at
least, came from the New World.

00:28:18.600 --> 00:28:21.920
And many people don't realize
what Italian food would be

00:28:21.920 --> 00:28:24.480
without tomato sauce,
prior to the 15th century.

00:28:24.480 --> 00:28:26.360
But, Domenica and I
actually have a colleague,

00:28:26.360 --> 00:28:28.380
who wrote a book called
<i>Beyond the Red Sauce</i>.

00:28:28.380 --> 00:28:29.780
His name is Chef Matt Finarelli.

00:28:29.780 --> 00:28:31.970
And it's all recipes
without tomato sauce,

00:28:31.970 --> 00:28:34.760
that were done prior
to the 15th century.

00:28:34.760 --> 00:28:36.920
So you can find that if
you're very interested.

00:28:36.920 --> 00:28:38.610
Another thing that we have to think

00:28:38.610 --> 00:28:41.800
about in Italian food
is the idea of realism.

00:28:41.800 --> 00:28:44.020
And the idea of showing
food like it is.

00:28:44.020 --> 00:28:45.750
And this kind of more
modern approach

00:28:45.750 --> 00:28:47.050
in the way that we eat today.

00:28:47.050 --> 00:28:49.380
And the way that we eat today,
even if you go to a restaurant

00:28:49.380 --> 00:28:51.000
and you look at a menu, it
will tell you the ingredients.

00:28:51.000 --> 00:28:52.490
It will say such-and-such salad.

00:28:52.490 --> 00:28:54.810
Then it will say
tomato/cucumber/onion,

00:28:54.810 --> 00:28:56.150
and we list the ingredients.

00:28:56.150 --> 00:28:57.560
That would not have
happened in the Renaissance.

00:28:57.560 --> 00:29:00.370
In the Renaissance, they would want
50 million different ingredients

00:29:00.370 --> 00:29:01.670
in there.

00:29:01.670 --> 00:29:03.360
You know, wrapped in a crust,
which has an animal in it.

00:29:03.360 --> 00:29:04.790
Which is stuffed with
something else.

00:29:04.790 --> 00:29:06.090
And really, you had to like guess.

00:29:06.090 --> 00:29:08.720
The food was like magic, and
a work of art, and a surprise,

00:29:08.720 --> 00:29:10.020
and these kind of things.

00:29:10.020 --> 00:29:11.320
So --

00:29:11.320 --> 00:29:12.620
&gt;&gt; Domenica Marchetti:
Okay, but I have --

00:29:12.620 --> 00:29:13.920
so, you're talking about
the Renaissance in Florence.

00:29:13.920 --> 00:29:15.220
&gt;&gt; Amy Riolo: Sure.

00:29:15.220 --> 00:29:16.520
&gt;&gt; Domenica Marchetti:
And all of that?

