So even though it has nothing
to do nowadays with risotto

00:30:56.180 --> 00:30:57.870
and what grows in the south.

00:30:57.870 --> 00:31:00.420
But you can see the
similarities from them,

00:31:00.420 --> 00:31:02.490
just because he got it
and he brought it in.

00:31:02.490 --> 00:31:04.910
So we have also our rice industry

00:31:04.910 --> 00:31:07.840
to thank Jefferson
and the Italians for.

00:31:07.840 --> 00:31:10.660
And here we are, Library
of Congress.

00:31:10.660 --> 00:31:12.930
Go around, you know, some
of the different buildings.

00:31:12.930 --> 00:31:17.950 position:56%
And you can see just how beautiful a
lot of the Italian architecture is.

00:31:17.950 --> 00:31:20.380
And here's when we start
to get more into the topic

00:31:20.380 --> 00:31:23.360
about the cucina povera, and that
whole thing, and how it started.

00:31:23.360 --> 00:31:27.970
So 1892 is when we really see the
mass immigration into the Americas.

00:31:27.970 --> 00:31:31.470
And as Italians, as, you know,
people who are studying Italy.

00:31:31.470 --> 00:31:32.770
Anybody who cares about
Italy at all,

00:31:32.770 --> 00:31:34.870
if you look at this time period,
that's all you're going to see.

00:31:34.870 --> 00:31:36.890
But there's a lot else
going on in Italy too.

00:31:36.890 --> 00:31:39.490
So we're going to present a
little bit of both of that today.

00:31:39.490 --> 00:31:41.280
So we see the, you know,
the immigration coming,

00:31:41.280 --> 00:31:43.470
and people leaving, and
people having to leave.

00:31:43.470 --> 00:31:45.360
And that, of course, changes a lot

00:31:45.360 --> 00:31:47.810
about what food is
known as, in the world.

00:31:47.810 --> 00:31:51.320
Here in America, if you study any
of the textbooks from, you know,

00:31:51.320 --> 00:31:53.410
what they were teaching in the
tenements and things like that.

00:31:53.410 --> 00:31:55.530
They would actually
send social workers

00:31:55.530 --> 00:31:57.450
to the Italian neighborhoods
in New York.

00:31:57.450 --> 00:31:59.600
And they would have them
come with their clipboards.

00:31:59.600 --> 00:32:01.310
And, you know, they would
like analyze the families.

00:32:01.310 --> 00:32:03.230
And they say, oh, you
know, you came from Italy

00:32:03.230 --> 00:32:04.530
and you've got these kids.

00:32:04.530 --> 00:32:06.120
And, you know, you're
just feeding them starch,

00:32:06.120 --> 00:32:07.980
and there's no protein,
and vegetables.

00:32:07.980 --> 00:32:09.610
That's not good, they
need meat and potatoes.

00:32:09.610 --> 00:32:10.960
They're not going to live.

00:32:10.960 --> 00:32:12.950
This is America, this is
what we do, we're advanced.

00:32:12.950 --> 00:32:16.280 position:56%
There was a lot of propaganda to
get people to eat meat and potatoes.

00:32:16.280 --> 00:32:19.140
So, in addition to poverty,
being new immigrants, you know,

00:32:19.140 --> 00:32:21.340
poor conditions, what
they were living in,

00:32:21.340 --> 00:32:22.840
and food not being available.

00:32:22.840 --> 00:32:25.560
They were also being told, this
is the way you have to eat.

00:32:25.560 --> 00:32:28.350
So, you know, if anybody every
criticizes what happened to the,

00:32:28.350 --> 00:32:29.980
you know, Italian-American food.

00:32:29.980 --> 00:32:33.410
There's a really strong reason
to it, and in a certain way,

00:32:33.410 --> 00:32:36.050
I think it's amazing that
so many food trends stayed,

00:32:36.050 --> 00:32:38.520
despite everything that
people went through.

00:32:38.520 --> 00:32:39.820
&gt;&gt; Domenica Marchetti: Right.

00:32:39.820 --> 00:32:41.120
&gt;&gt; Amy Riolo: Now, again,
at the same time, you know,

00:32:41.120 --> 00:32:42.550
not too much before, in Italy.

00:32:42.550 --> 00:32:45.230
As we're talking about
despair, and people talk

00:32:45.230 --> 00:32:46.580
about why people had to flee.

00:32:46.580 --> 00:32:49.460
There was also a lot of
very great things going on,

00:32:49.460 --> 00:32:51.150 position:56%
considering opera to be one of them.

00:32:51.150 --> 00:32:54.770
And Puccini was born
in 1858, in Lucca.

