00:34:08.840 --> 00:34:10.180
We have the pancotto.

00:34:10.180 --> 00:34:12.500
So the first two are
recipes made out of bread.

00:34:12.500 --> 00:34:16.360
So the pancotto on the bottom is
a soup made out of cooked bread.

00:34:16.360 --> 00:34:19.370
It's just leftover
bread made into a soup.

00:34:19.370 --> 00:34:21.420
You know, obviously very
cheap, inexpensive to make.

00:34:21.420 --> 00:34:25.270
But, when done well, there are
few things that taste as great.

00:34:25.270 --> 00:34:29.250 position:56%
And nowadays, a homemade, authentic,
honest stock is probably one

00:34:29.250 --> 00:34:32.190
of the biggest luxuries, I
think, you know, in humankind.

00:34:32.190 --> 00:34:35.050
Then we have the panzanella
salad, which leftover bread.

00:34:35.050 --> 00:34:36.600
People are taking advantage
of the good bread

00:34:36.600 --> 00:34:38.040
to turn it into the salad.

00:34:38.040 --> 00:34:41.540
And polenta, so polenta
comes from cornmeal.

00:34:41.540 --> 00:34:44.360
Corn, of course, was
brought back with Columbus,

00:34:44.360 --> 00:34:45.760
often called [foreign word].

00:34:45.760 --> 00:34:47.810
And made into this
dish called polenta.

00:34:47.810 --> 00:34:50.300
This is our Italian
version of grits.

00:34:50.300 --> 00:34:51.600
But people didn't like it.

00:34:51.600 --> 00:34:52.900
It didn't catch on very quickly.

00:34:52.900 --> 00:34:54.210
People were suspicious of
it, it looked like food

00:34:54.210 --> 00:34:55.760
that you would feed to the animals.

00:34:55.760 --> 00:34:57.690
And it really didn't have,
you know, much repertoire.

00:34:57.690 --> 00:34:59.840
But it caught on with the
Jewish community in the North,

00:34:59.840 --> 00:35:01.140
and they started eating it.

00:35:01.140 --> 00:35:03.600 position:56%
And then it, little by little, it
became a little bit more widespread.

00:35:03.600 --> 00:35:04.900
It spread to the south.

00:35:04.900 --> 00:35:06.200
And then in the south, a lot

00:35:06.200 --> 00:35:07.520
of the farmers started
eating it before they went

00:35:07.520 --> 00:35:08.820
out into the fields in the morning.

00:35:08.820 --> 00:35:10.120
So it would be a base.

00:35:10.120 --> 00:35:11.580
They would eat it with meat,
and they were these very big,

00:35:11.580 --> 00:35:13.940
untraditional, not what we
think of as Italian breakfasts.

00:35:13.940 --> 00:35:16.870
Because they had to work the
-- they had to work the land.

00:35:16.870 --> 00:35:20.660
And then in 1889, the
first pizzeria was born.

00:35:20.660 --> 00:35:22.330
So we all know, of
course, we don't have

00:35:22.330 --> 00:35:24.240
to tell anybody how
popular pizza is.

00:35:24.240 --> 00:35:26.900
But it's very important
that it has -- the pizzeria.

00:35:26.900 --> 00:35:30.740
And it's important that you look
at the Queen Margherita, and why,

00:35:30.740 --> 00:35:32.040
what she has to do with the pizza.

00:35:32.040 --> 00:35:33.650
Does anybody know this story?

00:35:33.650 --> 00:35:35.400
Okay. Okay, so some of you.

00:35:35.400 --> 00:35:36.970
So, you know, it was
a very humble food.

00:35:36.970 --> 00:35:38.270
It was a street food.

00:35:38.270 --> 00:35:40.200
It wasn't something that
the Queen would order.

00:35:40.200 --> 00:35:41.890
But, how they used to
sell the pizza was,

00:35:41.890 --> 00:35:44.320
if anybody's ever been
to Istanbul or Cairo.

00:35:44.320 --> 00:35:47.020
And you see the people walk around
with those big aluminum tanks

00:35:47.020 --> 00:35:49.370 position:56%
that are, they're getting water or
juice or something from these things

00:35:49.370 --> 00:35:50.670
that are strapped onto them.

00:35:50.670 --> 00:35:52.820
Well, they used to strap
ovens onto themselves, and go,

00:35:52.820 --> 00:35:54.120
they were like human vendors.

00:35:54.120 --> 00:35:56.210
And they would heat the pizza
up and sell it on the street.

00:35:56.210 --> 00:35:58.860
It was very, very poor,
you know, food.

00:35:58.860 --> 00:36:03.410 position:56%
And the Queen had a craving for one,
so she ordered one up to the castle.

00:36:03.410 --> 00:36:07.110
They made the tri-colored one for
her, in honor of the Italian flag.

00:36:07.110 --> 00:36:09.310
And this is how we got
the Margherita pizza.

00:36:09.310 --> 00:36:11.750
So you can still go to
visit this Pizzeria Brandi,

00:36:11.750 --> 00:36:13.980
if you go to Naples.

00:36:13.980 --> 00:36:15.490
And then also Verdi.

00:36:15.490 --> 00:36:17.480
So it's important to
think about opera,

00:36:17.480 --> 00:36:19.270
once again, at this time period.

00:36:19.270 --> 00:36:21.680
Because opera was so important,
and I do whole lectures

00:36:21.680 --> 00:36:23.390
on the influence of opera on food.

00:36:23.390 --> 00:36:27.220
But Verdi was very closely
associated with the Risorgimento.

00:36:27.220 --> 00:36:28.730
So his work was very political.

00:36:28.730 --> 00:36:30.470
And a lot of his writings

00:36:30.470 --> 00:36:33.760
and his music had understated
political, hidden messages.

00:36:33.760 --> 00:36:36.660
And these are important,
because at the same time,

00:36:36.660 --> 00:36:38.960
all of this unification
was going on in Italy.

00:36:38.960 --> 00:36:41.170
So there was a need for
unification of food.

00:36:41.170 --> 00:36:43.120
They were actually looking for food

00:36:43.120 --> 00:36:44.610
that would bring the
country together.

00:36:44.610 --> 00:36:46.680
Because, at the time, the
foods were all very regional

00:36:46.680 --> 00:36:47.980
and very different.

00:36:47.980 --> 00:36:49.820
And that's how we still like
to kind of look at it today.

00:36:49.820 --> 00:36:53.140
But they were looking, as
they were looking for a hero.

00:36:53.140 --> 00:36:55.910
A singer or a sports figure,
they also wanted food.

00:36:55.910 --> 00:36:58.850
And one of the things that
Verdi's legacy left was,

00:36:58.850 --> 00:37:02.070
he created some songs, and
popularized some songs,

00:37:02.070 --> 00:37:03.520
Italian songs around the world.

00:37:03.520 --> 00:37:06.010
That, you know, are,
people just hear the tune

00:37:06.010 --> 00:37:07.310
and they start humming them.

00:37:07.310 --> 00:37:08.610
And that's one of the many things

00:37:08.610 --> 00:37:11.060
that he gave us, in
terms of culture.

00:37:11.060 --> 00:37:13.960
So if you look at Milan in that
time, where the alla Scalla is,

00:37:13.960 --> 00:37:16.490
and the teatro, and
very fine dining.

00:37:16.490 --> 00:37:19.730 position:56%
And wonderful things are happening
there today, in terms of gastronomy.

00:37:19.730 --> 00:37:22.420
We can also, you know,
way back in his time,

00:37:22.420 --> 00:37:24.410
this wasn't that much
going on at that time.

00:37:24.410 --> 00:37:25.960 position:56%
So they had a lot of local products.

00:37:25.960 --> 00:37:27.550
They had the wonderful
dairy that they had,

00:37:27.550 --> 00:37:29.280
they had the farms
and things like that.

00:37:29.280 --> 00:37:33.330
Risotto, minestre, and
freshwater fish, this was the basis

00:37:33.330 --> 00:37:37.170
of what was going on
in Milan, at the time.

00:37:37.170 --> 00:37:39.230
And Verdi also has a
risotto named after him.

00:37:39.230 --> 00:37:41.780
So you can look this up
online, if you're a Verdi fan,

00:37:41.780 --> 00:37:45.260
and make this risotto when
you listen to the opera.

00:37:45.260 --> 00:37:47.940
But here are the regions, as
they are today, as I mentioned.

00:37:47.940 --> 00:37:50.510
So, you know, they weren't
exactly the same at that time.

00:37:50.510 --> 00:37:53.290
But you can see kind of the
differences, and how they evolved,

00:37:53.290 --> 00:37:55.630
and how they developed, and
what's unique to one another.

00:37:55.630 --> 00:37:58.580
Even within the regions, there are
still differences between the town.

00:37:58.580 --> 00:38:00.710
You know, a town one hour
away, two hours away,

00:38:00.710 --> 00:38:03.620
will have a different dialect,
different food, different terrain.

00:38:03.620 --> 00:38:05.310
And when you go, you get to see it.

00:38:05.310 --> 00:38:06.850
And this, as Domenica mentioned,

00:38:06.850 --> 00:38:09.500
really helped to shape the
different things of the food.

00:38:09.500 --> 00:38:11.700
So one region that we
know of very, very well,

00:38:11.700 --> 00:38:14.700
for food in the world today, is
the region of Emilia-Romagna.

00:38:14.700 --> 00:38:16.480
And especially the town of Parma.

00:38:16.480 --> 00:38:19.390
So Parmigiano-Reggiano is the
most famous cheese from there,

00:38:19.390 --> 00:38:21.320
and the most famous cheese
known around the world.

00:38:21.320 --> 00:38:24.380
It's said that Benjamin Franklin
even tried to get the recipe.

00:38:24.380 --> 00:38:26.320 position:56%
And it has an eight-century history.

00:38:26.320 --> 00:38:29.740
Very meticulous process of what
they have to do to make it.

00:38:29.740 --> 00:38:32.400
And it's all governed by
the government and all

00:38:32.400 --> 00:38:33.700
of these types of consortiums.

00:38:33.700 --> 00:38:36.540 position:56%
So you know you were getting an
authentic product when you go there.

00:38:36.540 --> 00:38:39.470
For those of you who like the
Prosciutto di Parma, the --

00:38:39.470 --> 00:38:42.180
sorry for the small p on the Parma.

00:38:42.180 --> 00:38:45.240
For those of you who like it, you
will find that one of the things

00:38:45.240 --> 00:38:49.040
that makes it unique, is that the
pigs are fed the leftover whey

00:38:49.040 --> 00:38:50.650 position:56%
from making the Parmigiano-Reggiano.

00:38:50.650 --> 00:38:52.830
That's one of the reasons
why it gets so much flavor,

00:38:52.830 --> 00:38:54.970
in addition to the different
breeds and the different things.

00:38:54.970 --> 00:38:57.610
These types of food
traditions are one of the things

00:38:57.610 --> 00:38:59.280
that helps the Italian economy.

00:38:59.280 --> 00:39:01.010
That helps the gastronomy
around the world,

00:39:01.010 --> 00:39:03.950
and it helps what makes the
Made in Italy brand strong.

00:39:03.950 --> 00:39:07.220
So nowadays, one of the things
that we're doing is really trying

00:39:07.220 --> 00:39:09.290
to promote geographic indicators.

00:39:09.290 --> 00:39:11.900
A lot of times, people will come
and will have events here in D.C.

00:39:11.900 --> 00:39:14.610
from Switzerland, and from
U.N. and different places.

00:39:14.610 --> 00:39:16.880
If we can protect, for
example, the Idaho potato,

00:39:16.880 --> 00:39:19.830
and the Prosciutto di
Parma, and things like this,

00:39:19.830 --> 00:39:22.920
different economies do better.

00:39:22.920 --> 00:39:24.780
You know, there's a lot
more increased trade.

00:39:24.780 --> 00:39:27.160
People know what they're buying
and they get authentic products.

00:39:27.160 --> 00:39:30.270
So it's a thing of the
future, that to look at.

00:39:30.270 --> 00:39:32.210
But getting back to the
unification of Italy.

00:39:32.210 --> 00:39:34.180
So Garibaldi, who is
probably, you know,

00:39:34.180 --> 00:39:37.060
considered to be the father
of the [foreign word].

00:39:37.060 --> 00:39:39.120
And very important General
in the Italian Army,

00:39:39.120 --> 00:39:41.140
and in causing the
unification of Italy.

00:39:41.140 --> 00:39:43.910
He first ate Spaghetti
al Pomodoro in Calabria,

00:39:43.910 --> 00:39:46.160
at this place that
you see over there.

00:39:46.160 --> 00:39:47.590
Melito di Porto Salvo.

00:39:47.590 --> 00:39:49.670
And he said to the
soldiers, "I swear to you,

00:39:49.670 --> 00:39:51.950
this will be the dish
that unifies Italy."

00:39:51.950 --> 00:39:54.490
So for those of us who,
like, when we see the dish,

00:39:54.490 --> 00:39:56.200
and we're like oh, no,
it's stereotypical.

00:39:56.200 --> 00:39:58.880
It's not. Garibaldi endorsed it.

00:39:58.880 --> 00:40:00.180
That's all we need.

00:40:00.180 --> 00:40:01.480 position:56%
We can have it for 5,000 more years.

00:40:01.480 --> 00:40:04.530
And then, of course, we start
to see the mass-produced pasta.

00:40:04.530 --> 00:40:07.150
And, you know, why was there such
a need for mass-produced pasta?

00:40:07.150 --> 00:40:09.980
Well, this is when people
really started leaving Italy.

00:40:09.980 --> 00:40:11.280
So they're leaving Italy.

00:40:11.280 --> 00:40:13.990
They can't bring with them
their pasta making tools, maybe.

00:40:13.990 --> 00:40:16.140
They don't have maybe the new
ingredients to make pasta.

00:40:16.140 --> 00:40:17.440
They're going to need pasta.

00:40:17.440 --> 00:40:18.740
And one of the things

00:40:18.740 --> 00:40:21.140
that [inaudible] the
way of packaged pasta.

00:40:21.140 --> 00:40:23.780
And pasta chuta, as we call
it, dried pasta in the world,

00:40:23.780 --> 00:40:26.590
is this mass immigration.

00:40:26.590 --> 00:40:30.550
So then we have this invention
of Italian-American cuisine.

00:40:30.550 --> 00:40:34.920 position:56%
So nowadays, what people were
eating, maybe on a Sunday, in Italy,

00:40:34.920 --> 00:40:37.050
as a, you know, luxury food.

00:40:37.050 --> 00:40:40.000 position:56%
We're eating more and more
commonly as a daily food in America,

00:40:40.000 --> 00:40:41.300
because meat is cheap here.

00:40:41.300 --> 00:40:42.700
Meat still is cheaper than herbs.

00:40:42.700 --> 00:40:45.310
And then a lot of vegetables,
and very easy to get.

00:40:45.310 --> 00:40:48.560
You know, dandelion greens, which
we used to eat by the bushel-full

00:40:48.560 --> 00:40:50.270
when I was a kid, are expensive.

00:40:50.270 --> 00:40:52.350
Meat, on the other hand, is cheap.

00:40:52.350 --> 00:40:55.760 position:56%
And so there's a sort of, there's a,
you know, health component to that.

00:40:55.760 --> 00:40:58.940
Because you have, the name
for dandelion, in Latin,

00:40:58.940 --> 00:41:00.850
is official disease remedy.

00:41:00.850 --> 00:41:02.290
And they're expensive.

00:41:02.290 --> 00:41:03.590
So, but --

