00:41:31.790 --> 00:41:34.310
&gt;&gt; Amy Riolo: And then, in 1891,
there's a book that we actually,

00:41:34.310 --> 00:41:36.970
Lucia provided for us
out there, you can see.

00:41:36.970 --> 00:41:39.230
<i>La Scienza en cucina e
l'arte di mangiar bene</i>.

00:41:39.230 --> 00:41:41.680
This was a very important
book, written by Artusi,

00:41:41.680 --> 00:41:43.340
that all the Italian chefs study.

00:41:43.340 --> 00:41:45.680
And anybody who's interested in
Italian food should look at it.

00:41:45.680 --> 00:41:48.080
Because it talks about
verismo in the kitchen.

00:41:48.080 --> 00:41:50.500
So again, this ideal of
realism, like we were talking

00:41:50.500 --> 00:41:52.600
about with Titian and
Caravaggio comes in.

00:41:52.600 --> 00:41:54.640
And this was written
for the middle classes.

00:41:54.640 --> 00:41:57.960 position:56%
So, unlike Apicius, who was
writing for, you know, the emperors,

00:41:57.960 --> 00:41:59.260
and he was a philosopher.

00:41:59.260 --> 00:42:01.140
And unlike, later on,
people who were writing

00:42:01.140 --> 00:42:03.040
for the cooks of the kings.

00:42:03.040 --> 00:42:05.700
He was actually writing
for the middle classes.

00:42:05.700 --> 00:42:07.770
&gt;&gt; Domenica Macchetti: And,
one thing about Artusi is

00:42:07.770 --> 00:42:10.510
that he was from, I
think, Emilia-Romagna,

00:42:10.510 --> 00:42:12.500
but lived for years in Florence.

00:42:12.500 --> 00:42:14.840
So I guess the majority
of the recipes

00:42:14.840 --> 00:42:16.250
in his book were from that region.

00:42:16.250 --> 00:42:20.460
But he did gather recipes
from around the peninsula.

00:42:20.460 --> 00:42:23.420
And so that was kind
of considered maybe one

00:42:23.420 --> 00:42:25.480
of the first regional cookbooks.

00:42:25.480 --> 00:42:31.030
And it helped to unify, you know,
what we know of as Italian cuisine.

00:42:31.030 --> 00:42:32.330
&gt;&gt; Amy Riolo: That's
a really good point.

00:42:32.330 --> 00:42:33.630
That's a very good point.

00:42:33.630 --> 00:42:35.880
Because, prior to that, the
books would have been, you know,

00:42:35.880 --> 00:42:37.180
from wherever they were written.

00:42:37.180 --> 00:42:38.480
Or from wherever the
author was written.

00:42:38.480 --> 00:42:41.540
In the 19th century, so with the
continuing changes that we see,

00:42:41.540 --> 00:42:44.550
are a lot more lighter,
more fresh ingredients.

00:42:44.550 --> 00:42:46.750
Again, we're getting away
from those heavily spiced,

00:42:46.750 --> 00:42:49.940
really intricate recipes
of the Renaissance.

00:42:49.940 --> 00:42:51.430
Then comes along Puccini.

00:42:51.430 --> 00:42:55.280
And now we're seeing verismo in
this idea of realism in the opera.

00:42:55.280 --> 00:42:57.630
And Puccini talking about
very middle-class scenes.

00:42:57.630 --> 00:42:59.510
And very everyday things
that you can see.

00:42:59.510 --> 00:43:02.130
And not trying to be so elevated.

00:43:02.130 --> 00:43:05.260
This, again, is something
that transformed

00:43:05.260 --> 00:43:06.560
and it shows in the kitchen.

00:43:06.560 --> 00:43:09.100
And then also, Puccini,
because of his success,

00:43:09.100 --> 00:43:11.490
and because of the different
global things that he talked about.

00:43:11.490 --> 00:43:12.790
He had things set in Asia.

00:43:12.790 --> 00:43:14.290
He had things set in Paris.

00:43:14.290 --> 00:43:16.680
So against the backdrop
of this mass immigration,

00:43:16.680 --> 00:43:18.690
and people aren't afforded to live.

00:43:18.690 --> 00:43:21.230
You also have people who are
really upholding the high end

00:43:21.230 --> 00:43:22.530
of Italian culture.

00:43:22.530 --> 00:43:25.280
And telling people, okay, this
is really what we're capable of,

00:43:25.280 --> 00:43:29.510
in addition to some of the
problems that are going on.

00:43:29.510 --> 00:43:31.710
Then we have the futurist
movement in food.

00:43:31.710 --> 00:43:33.410
And I know you're going to be
