they're very whimsical.

00:53:41.470 --> 00:53:44.840
And some are traditional,
but many these days are not

00:53:44.840 --> 00:53:46.140
traditional anymore.

00:53:46.140 --> 00:53:49.520
I mean, there's a shape
now that I see

00:53:49.520 --> 00:53:50.890
in stores, called the calamarata.

00:53:50.890 --> 00:53:52.710
And it looks like a calamari ring

00:53:52.710 --> 00:53:54.510
and you serve it with
a seafood sauce.

00:53:54.510 --> 00:53:57.080
But, you know, when I was
growing up, that didn't exist.

00:53:57.080 --> 00:54:00.010
So I don't know if
there's an answer.

00:54:00.010 --> 00:54:01.310
I would say hundreds.

00:54:01.310 --> 00:54:03.490
I mean, yeah, honestly.

00:54:03.490 --> 00:54:06.910
&gt;&gt; Amy Riolo: But also,
sometimes people take pastas

00:54:06.910 --> 00:54:09.430
that are traditionally made fresh.

00:54:09.430 --> 00:54:11.970
And they make them into a
dry pasta, or vice versa.

00:54:11.970 --> 00:54:13.270
&gt;&gt; Domenica Marchetti: Right.

00:54:13.270 --> 00:54:14.570
&gt;&gt; Amy Riolo: One that's
normally dry, then they'll start,

00:54:14.570 --> 00:54:16.030
in a restaurant, they'll say,
oh, we want to do that fresh.

00:54:16.030 --> 00:54:17.970
But in Italy, there
might not be a tradition

00:54:17.970 --> 00:54:20.860
of making that pasta fresh.

00:54:20.860 --> 00:54:24.020
That happens too.

00:54:24.020 --> 00:54:25.320
&gt;&gt; Domenica Marchetti: Yeah.

00:54:25.320 --> 00:54:30.160
&gt;&gt; And the second part
of my question is,

00:54:30.160 --> 00:54:33.020
exactly what does antipasto mean?

00:54:33.020 --> 00:54:37.280
And why is it called -- why is
mortadella called mortadella?

00:54:37.280 --> 00:54:38.580
&gt;&gt; Domenica Marchetti:
So antipasto is --

00:54:38.580 --> 00:54:40.200
anti is before, pasta,
before the meal.

00:54:40.200 --> 00:54:41.510 position:56%
So it's your appetizer, essentially.

00:54:41.510 --> 00:54:43.820
And mortadella is called
mortadella because, I don't know.

00:54:43.820 --> 00:54:45.120
Do you?

00:54:45.120 --> 00:54:46.420
[ Laughter ]

00:54:46.420 --> 00:54:47.720
Does anybody know?

00:54:47.720 --> 00:54:49.020
I'd love to know that.

00:54:49.020 --> 00:54:50.320
That's a good one.

00:54:50.320 --> 00:54:51.620
I'll --

00:54:51.620 --> 00:54:52.920
&gt;&gt; We'll research it.

00:54:52.920 --> 00:54:54.220
&gt;&gt; Domenica Marchetti: Yeah.

00:54:54.220 --> 00:54:55.520
&gt;&gt; [Inaudible] Something like that.

00:54:55.520 --> 00:54:56.820
But it's delicious.

00:54:56.820 --> 00:54:58.120
&gt;&gt; Domenica Marchetti:
Yeah, I don't know.

00:54:58.120 --> 00:54:59.420
That's a great question.

00:54:59.420 --> 00:55:00.720
&gt;&gt; First of all, I want
to thank you, both of you,

00:55:00.720 --> 00:55:02.020
for these illuminating speeches.

00:55:02.020 --> 00:55:03.320
Are wonderful to hear
from you all about Italy.

00:55:03.320 --> 00:55:05.170
[Inaudible] so we don't
know never enough, you know.

00:55:05.170 --> 00:55:07.530
So I do have a question.

00:55:07.530 --> 00:55:14.920
So when I grew up in the
restaurants, my mother was a chef,

00:55:14.920 --> 00:55:17.040
my grandmother was a chef.

00:55:17.040 --> 00:55:20.290
I'm not a chef, but I eat
it a lot, and we are --

00:55:20.290 --> 00:55:21.590
&gt;&gt; Domenica Marchetti:
Where, in Italy?

00:55:21.590 --> 00:55:22.890
&gt;&gt; Liguria.

00:55:22.890 --> 00:55:24.190 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Domenica Marchetti: Oh, the best.

00:55:24.190 --> 00:55:25.490
Wonderful.

00:55:25.490 --> 00:55:27.090 position:56%
&gt;&gt; So when I moved here ten years
ago, and every day mostly that I go.

00:55:27.090 --> 00:55:29.710
Like today, [inaudible] invite me
for lunch in an Italian restaurant.

00:55:29.710 --> 00:55:32.090
And it's the most awful
thing [inaudible].

00:55:32.090 --> 00:55:38.170
I see on the menu, pasta
with Alfredo sauce.

00:55:38.170 --> 00:55:39.470
Where is this coming from?

00:55:39.470 --> 00:55:40.770
Because we don't have that.

00:55:40.770 --> 00:55:42.070
I never have in Italy,
have Alfredo sauce.

00:55:42.070 --> 00:55:43.370
And here it's everywhere,
in the [inaudible].

00:55:43.370 --> 00:55:44.670
So can you please help me to --

00:55:44.670 --> 00:55:45.970
&gt;&gt; Domenica Marchetti: So
that's a great question.

00:55:45.970 --> 00:55:48.290
I know it's not Italian.

00:55:48.290 --> 00:55:49.590
&gt;&gt; No.

00:55:49.590 --> 00:55:51.550
&gt;&gt; Domenica Marchetti:
And I'm surprised to hear

00:55:51.550 --> 00:55:52.940
that places still serve it.

00:55:52.940 --> 00:55:56.300 position:56%
Because I had mentioned that I think
a lot of chefs are really trying

00:55:56.300 --> 00:55:58.490
to do justice to Italian food.

00:55:58.490 --> 00:56:00.070
Using local ingredients, but --

00:56:00.070 --> 00:56:02.120
[ Inaudible Comment from Audience ]

00:56:02.120 --> 00:56:03.910
So, do you know the story?

00:56:03.910 --> 00:56:06.200
&gt;&gt; Amy Riolo: Yeah,
the popular story,

00:56:06.200 --> 00:56:07.760
whether it's lore or real or not.

00:56:07.760 --> 00:56:10.670
Was in the early part of
the 20th century, in Rome,

00:56:10.670 --> 00:56:12.660
a lot of the actors and
actresses were going there.

00:56:12.660 --> 00:56:16.070 position:56%
And Mary Pickford, who is a
prominent silent film star, actress,

00:56:16.070 --> 00:56:17.370
here in the United States.

00:56:17.370 --> 00:56:19.770
Went to one of the Roman chefs
and asked for something like,

00:56:19.770 --> 00:56:22.810
similar to like [foreign
word], but with cream.

00:56:22.810 --> 00:56:24.120
And so they made that for her.

00:56:24.120 --> 00:56:26.860
And apparently, his name was
Alfredo, and the recipe came

00:56:26.860 --> 00:56:28.160
to be known as Alfredo sauce.

00:56:28.160 --> 00:56:30.260
So even though it's not an Italian
recipe that people would eat

00:56:30.260 --> 00:56:33.640
and enjoy at home, it came back
here because she was Mary Pickford.

00:56:33.640 --> 00:56:35.760
So it got introduced
as an Italian recipe.

00:56:35.760 --> 00:56:37.060
&gt;&gt; Right, okay.

00:56:37.060 --> 00:56:38.360
Thank you so much.

00:56:38.360 --> 00:56:39.660
[ Multiple Speakers ]

00:56:39.660 --> 00:56:40.960
&gt;&gt; Domenica Marchetti: Yeah.

00:56:40.960 --> 00:56:42.260
&gt;&gt; -- You know, when
other people go.

00:56:42.260 --> 00:56:45.040
&gt;&gt; Domenica Marchetti: There
are other dishes like that.

00:56:45.040 --> 00:56:46.340
Yes.

00:56:46.340 --> 00:56:47.640
&gt;&gt; Susan Finstead [phonetic].

00:56:47.640 --> 00:56:57.850
It's such a pleasure to be
here and to learn about this.

00:56:57.850 --> 00:57:04.720
Not to say anything
except something good.

00:57:04.720 --> 00:57:09.330
Are there places that you
can recommend in Washington,

00:57:09.330 --> 00:57:11.820
D.C., to get Italian food?

00:57:11.820 --> 00:57:16.910
That isn't Italian style, but would
be something that would seem to you

00:57:16.910 --> 00:57:20.150
to be what you would enjoy?

00:57:20.150 --> 00:57:23.120
&gt;&gt; Domenica Marchetti: I
can tell you what I enjoy.

00:57:23.120 --> 00:57:27.030
And it's not like going to a
restaurant in Italy, necessarily.

00:57:27.030 --> 00:57:29.580
But, like I said, I do think

00:57:29.580 --> 00:57:32.850
that chefs are really
trying to do justice.

00:57:32.850 --> 00:57:36.690
Now, I haven't been
in a number of years.

00:57:36.690 --> 00:57:41.080
But Obelisk is, you know, said to
be a good Italian restaurant here

00:57:41.080 --> 00:57:43.720
in D.C. That's been
around for a long time.

00:57:43.720 --> 00:57:48.150
I am a fan of Michael Schlow's
restaurant, Alta Strada.

00:57:48.150 --> 00:57:52.000
Which, yeah, Alta Strada, which is
on K Street, and that's pretty new.

00:57:52.000 --> 00:57:55.540
And he's opened a seafood
restaurant called Casolare.

00:57:55.540 --> 00:57:58.010
So those are a couple.

00:57:58.010 --> 00:57:59.670
Nick Stefanelli, in,
near Union Market,

00:57:59.670 --> 00:58:03.550 position:56%
has a restaurant called Masseria,
which is very high-end, but Italian.

00:58:03.550 --> 00:58:07.790
And also high-end, are
the Fiola and Fiola Mare.

00:58:07.790 --> 00:58:10.830
So are they, I mean, and
the Chef from Fiola is

00:58:10.830 --> 00:58:12.130
from Le Marche, Fabio Trabocchi.

00:58:12.130 --> 00:58:14.940
So, you know, you can get --
it's still not, to me, I mean,

00:58:14.940 --> 00:58:16.240
the food at these places, I
think is really wonderful.

00:58:16.240 --> 00:58:17.540
It's not like going to,
you know, an agriturismo

00:58:17.540 --> 00:58:18.840
in the Maiella mountains.

00:58:18.840 --> 00:58:20.140
Which is like what I
like to do when I'm --

00:58:20.140 --> 00:58:21.600
[ Laughter ]

00:58:21.600 --> 00:58:24.320
-- But, yeah.

00:58:24.320 --> 00:58:26.890
I think there's -- do you have --

00:58:26.890 --> 00:58:28.190
&gt;&gt; Amy Riolo: I also
recommend Al Tiramisu

00:58:28.190 --> 00:58:31.660 position:56%
on P Street, and Aperto on I Street.

00:58:31.660 --> 00:58:33.830
&gt;&gt; Domenica Marchetti: Right,
and he's from Basilicata, right?

00:58:33.830 --> 00:58:35.130
&gt;&gt; Amy Riolo: Yes.

00:58:35.130 --> 00:58:36.430
&gt;&gt; Domenica Marchetti: So
he's from Italy as well.

00:58:36.430 --> 00:58:37.730
Yeah.

00:58:37.730 --> 00:58:39.030
&gt;&gt; Amy Riolo: You had a question.

00:58:39.030 --> 00:58:40.440
&gt;&gt; You pointed out the regional
variations of food in Italy.

00:58:40.440 --> 00:58:45.690
Well, of course, Italian-American
food is very varied too.

00:58:45.690 --> 00:58:47.110
Especially like pizza.

00:58:47.110 --> 00:58:49.510
Like, I swear by New Haven Pizza,

00:58:49.510 --> 00:58:51.680
especially with the
white clam sauce.

00:58:51.680 --> 00:58:55.990
But, versus that bread in Chicago.

00:58:55.990 --> 00:58:57.290
&gt;&gt; Domenica Marchetti:
Deep-dish pizza.

00:58:57.290 --> 00:58:58.590
Yeah, yeah.

00:58:58.590 --> 00:59:02.420
&gt;&gt; And, of course, Detroit
style pizza and St. Louis pizza.

00:59:02.420 --> 00:59:05.100
Of course, in St. Louis,
they fry the ravioli.

00:59:05.100 --> 00:59:06.400
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:59:06.400 --> 00:59:07.700
&gt;&gt; Domenica Marchetti: Yeah, so
there are regional differences

00:59:07.700 --> 00:59:09.480
in Italian-American
cuisine, for sure.

00:59:09.480 --> 00:59:10.780
Yeah.

00:59:10.780 --> 00:59:12.280 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Are any of them popular in Italy?

00:59:12.280 --> 00:59:13.630
&gt;&gt; Domenica Marchetti:
Not that I know of.

00:59:13.630 --> 00:59:15.680
[ Laughter and Multiple Speakers ]

00:59:15.680 --> 00:59:16.980
I don't think they're popular.

00:59:16.980 --> 00:59:19.380
There is some -- I
did see somewhere,

00:59:19.380 --> 00:59:21.970
that there is an Italian-American
restaurant that has --

00:59:21.970 --> 00:59:23.270
&gt;&gt; Amy Riolo: In Rome

00:59:23.270 --> 00:59:24.570
&gt;&gt; Domenica Marchetti: In Rome?

00:59:24.570 --> 00:59:25.870
I thought it was Milano.

00:59:25.870 --> 00:59:27.170
Really?

00:59:27.170 --> 00:59:28.470
&gt;&gt; Amy Riolo: Maybe both.

00:59:28.470 --> 00:59:29.770
Maybe both.

00:59:29.770 --> 00:59:31.070
&gt;&gt; Domenica Marchetti: So --

00:59:31.070 --> 00:59:32.370
&gt;&gt; Amy Riolo: I've
seen the Rome one.

00:59:32.370 --> 00:59:33.670
&gt;&gt; Domenica Marchetti: So
the food came back here

00:59:33.670 --> 00:59:34.970
and now it's gone back there.

00:59:34.970 --> 00:59:36.270
I'd be curious to try it.

00:59:36.270 --> 00:59:37.570
I, you know, maybe, I don't know.

00:59:37.570 --> 00:59:38.870
Yeah. Yes.

00:59:38.870 --> 00:59:40.170
&gt;&gt; I have a question.

00:59:40.170 --> 00:59:42.080
When I lived in Italy, or when I
first, you know, lived in Italy.

00:59:42.080 --> 00:59:44.840
I was told a lot of
things, like first of all,

00:59:44.840 --> 00:59:48.080
you do not order cappuccino
after noon.

00:59:48.080 --> 00:59:50.000
&gt;&gt; Domenica Marchetti:
That's right, that's right.

00:59:50.000 --> 00:59:53.510
&gt;&gt; Never, ever, and that kind
of tags you as an American.

00:59:53.510 --> 00:59:54.810
Or, you know, a non-Italian.

00:59:54.810 --> 00:59:56.110
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:59:56.110 --> 00:59:58.800
&gt;&gt; And the second thing was that
you never, ever put grated cheese

00:59:58.800 --> 01:00:01.750
on seafood pasta or mushroom pasta.

01:00:01.750 --> 01:00:03.120
&gt;&gt; Domenica Marchetti:
Mushroom, yes.

01:00:03.120 --> 01:00:08.200
&gt;&gt; But, is that a practice, is
there some kind of rule about this?

01:00:08.200 --> 01:00:10.510
&gt;&gt; Domenica Marchetti: Yes,
and best not to question it.

01:00:10.510 --> 01:00:13.550
[ Laughter ]

01:00:13.550 --> 01:00:16.950
You know, cappuccino
is a breakfast drink.

01:00:16.950 --> 01:00:18.340
If you have it in the afternoon,

01:00:18.340 --> 01:00:20.400
it'll sit in your stomach
like a stone.

01:00:20.400 --> 01:00:23.180
You know, that's what
I think the Italian --

01:00:23.180 --> 01:00:25.400
but we all have our own habits.

01:00:25.400 --> 01:00:28.010
I mean, here, we drink,
you know, coffee, or the --

01:00:28.010 --> 01:00:29.310
[ Foreign Language ]

01:00:29.310 --> 01:00:33.550
-- I don't know how big,
Starbucks, you know.

01:00:33.550 --> 01:00:38.960
And then I think there are rare
exceptions with the seafood.

01:00:38.960 --> 01:00:41.930
And I thought of one the other
day, and now it escapes me.

01:00:41.930 --> 01:00:46.340
But, in general, seafood
doesn't call for cheese.

01:00:46.340 --> 01:00:49.380
They just clash of flavors.

01:00:49.380 --> 01:00:53.360
And does anybody have a more
specific answer to that?

01:00:53.360 --> 01:00:55.760
&gt;&gt; Amy Riolo: Yeah, well not
more to that, but just to add on.

01:00:55.760 --> 01:00:57.060
There are so many more.

01:00:57.060 --> 01:00:59.950
And that's one of the
things that, when people try

01:00:59.950 --> 01:01:01.250
to learn about Italian food.

01:01:01.250 --> 01:01:03.010 position:56%
Is that they might learn how to make
a recipe, or they might learn how

01:01:03.010 --> 01:01:04.310
to make two or three things.

01:01:04.310 --> 01:01:06.230
But even pairing them
together, when to serve them,

01:01:06.230 --> 01:01:08.150
or what goes together,
is so difficult.

01:01:08.150 --> 01:01:11.210 position:56%
So one of my main objectives for the
series I'm going to teach next year.

01:01:11.210 --> 01:01:14.870
For example, in a course, you would
never have soup and then pasta.

01:01:14.870 --> 01:01:17.140
It's soup or pasta,
as a first course.

01:01:17.140 --> 01:01:19.780
And but there, sometimes I find
American chefs doing Italian food,

01:01:19.780 --> 01:01:21.470
and they'll have like
a prefixed menu.

01:01:21.470 --> 01:01:23.940
It's like soup, and then
pasta, and then, you know,

01:01:23.940 --> 01:01:26.480
and it's really, it's
strange to see it.

01:01:26.480 --> 01:01:29.710
It's -- and I once described
it to one of my editors as,

01:01:29.710 --> 01:01:32.670
you putting these together in a
picture, is like putting a corndog

01:01:32.670 --> 01:01:34.410
on a silver platter on
an American cookbook.

01:01:34.410 --> 01:01:35.910
Like, nobody would do it.

01:01:35.910 --> 01:01:37.460
So there are a lot of things.

01:01:37.460 --> 01:01:38.760
It takes time.

01:01:38.760 --> 01:01:40.130
And when you're there,
you learn them.

01:01:40.130 --> 01:01:42.230
And you could get little
by little, in cookbooks.

01:01:42.230 --> 01:01:44.190
But I don't think anybody
has ever done one thing

01:01:44.190 --> 01:01:45.490
that has like all the rules.

01:01:45.490 --> 01:01:46.790
You know, that would be fun.

01:01:46.790 --> 01:01:49.830 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Domenica Marchetti: That would be
fun, and a very complicated process.

01:01:49.830 --> 01:01:51.130
&gt;&gt; Yeah, [inaudible].

01:01:51.130 --> 01:01:53.830
&gt;&gt; Amy Riolo: Very controversial.

01:01:53.830 --> 01:01:56.130
Any other questions.

01:01:58.040 --> 01:01:59.340
Well, we thank you all for --

01:01:59.340 --> 01:02:01.140
&gt;&gt; Domenica Marchetti: Yeah, thank
you so much for coming, everybody.

